---
import MainLayout from '../../../layouts/MainLayout.astro';
import MotuSidebar from '../../../components/MotuSidebar.astro';
const title = "Hybrid FireWire/USB2";
---
<MainLayout title={title}>
  <div class="flex gap-8 items-start">
    <div class="w-[250px] flex-shrink-0">
      <MotuSidebar />
    </div>
    <article class="prose max-w-none">
      <h1>{title}</h1>
      <p>Source: <a href="https://motu.com/products/motuaudio/ultralite-mk3/hybrid.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener">MOTU product page</a></p>
      <p>The official MOTU Hybrid FireWire/USB2 page presents the UltraLite-mk3 as one of the first audio interfaces to offer both FireWire and hi-speed USB2 connectivity in the same unit. The emphasis is on flexibility: you can connect to older FireWire-based systems or newer USB2-equipped computers without changing the overall workflow.</p>
      <figure>
        <img src="https://cdn-data.motu.com/site/images/ultralite-mk3/hybrid-sm.png" alt="UltraLite-mk3 Hybrid logo" />
        <figcaption>Hybrid branding image used on the official MOTU page.</figcaption>
      </figure>

      <p>MOTU describes FireWire as a long-established high-performance connection for professional audio interfaces and notes that their FireWire interfaces are compatible with FireWire 800-equipped Macs by using a standard FireWire 400-to-800 cable. At the same time, USB2 support extends compatibility to systems that do not have FireWire ports.</p>

      <p>The page also explains the practical difference between the two connection types. If a computer has both, the choice comes down to the setup and whether bus power matters. FireWire can power the UltraLite-mk3 Hybrid directly from the computer, while USB2 requires the included DC power supply because USB alone does not provide enough power for the unit.</p>

      <h2>Flexible connection options</h2>
      <p>To support both standards, the interface includes a FireWire A 400 Mbit/sec connector and a hi-speed USB2 480 Mbit/sec connector. MOTU positions this as a way to maximize compatibility with a wide range of Mac and Windows systems without sacrificing the low-latency, high-bandwidth behavior expected from a dedicated audio interface.</p>

      <h2>Bus power vs external power</h2>
      <p>The official page makes one operational distinction especially clear: FireWire can bus-power the UltraLite-mk3 Hybrid, but USB2 cannot. For portable or simplified setups, that makes FireWire the more convenient option when it is available, while USB2 remains the fallback for modern machines that no longer include FireWire hardware.</p>
    </article>
  </div>
</MainLayout>
